[{"title": "YouTube TV listened to sports fans, and it\u2019s fixing multiview\u2019s biggest problem", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A screenshot of YouTube TV\u2019s multiview feature\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/UQO-hdfxN9VxY18hz8KPh9QbxuM=/0x0:640x427/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73098567/youtube_tv_screenshot.0.png\" />\n        <figcaption><em>Fantasy players and sports bettors should be salivating right now.</em> | YouTube</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"OOOT4z\">Since its launch last spring, <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2023/3/14/23638949/youtube-tv-multiview-early-access\">YouTube TV\u2019s multiview functionality</a> has been a huge quality-of-life improvement for sports fans. You can use it to watch multiple games concurrently without making space for extra TVs \u2014 but until now, you could only watch the predetermined sets of games that YouTube thinks would appeal to most viewers. An incoming update changes that, finally letting you customize multiview with your preferred combination of broadcasts, as spotted by <a href=\"https://9to5google.com/20", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T22:54:03+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055945/youtube-tv-multiview-customization-sports-news-weather", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Spec Ops: The Line permanently removed from Steam and other digital stores", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Screenshot from Spec Ops: The Line featuring the game\u2019s protagonist in tactical gear wielding a rifle staring at a urban city covered by sand.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/su5Ol7gel6mxr6AB2gTsfBrRkbY=/100x0:1180x720/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73098467/3b67ad95d86eed9123b3b4a8cc7e6ad1fb5dbb51dc126bbbda89a1ac2f172b81.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: 2K</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"awuEat\">We finally know <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055810/even-spec-ops-the-lines-developers-dont-know-whats-going-on\">why <em>Spec Ops: The Line</em> was delisted</a> \u2014 it\u2019s the licensing. Video game newshound Wario64 first sounded the alarm on social media <a href=\"https://x.com/Wario64/status/1752100767589347450?s=20\">that the game had been removed</a> from Steam and other PC storefronts seemingly without explanation. </p>\n<p id=\"KUYb2m\">On X, Cory Davis, the game\u2019s designer and director, was also out of the l", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T22:29:44+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055807/spec-ops-the-line-delisting-licensing-2k", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Elon Musk won\u2019t get his $55 billion pay package after all", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Elon Musk stands, frowning, in front of flame emoji\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/oH1aWC1vL-lkesms7YZh7WGH128=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73098361/VRG_Illo_STK022_K_Radtke_Musk_Stock_Fire_Sad.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Kristen Radtke / The Verge; Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"ymkE5f\">Elon Musk isn\u2019t going to get that $55 billion pay package after all, <a href=\"https://courts.delaware.gov/Opinions/Download.aspx?id=359340\">a Delaware Chancery Court judge has ruled</a>.</p>\n<p id=\"S3GbXf\">Tesla shareholders approved the package in 2018, which gave Musk incentive to hit specific milestones, including a market valuation of $650 billion, <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/23/16922758/elon-musk-compensation-tesla\">which was more than 10 times the valuation at the time</a>. The trial hinged on a specific question: did Musk mislead the shareholders when he gave them the", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T22:01:43+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24056177/elon-musk-tesla-tornetta-55-billion-pay-package-rejected", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Some suggested events for Peter Thiel\u2019s all-drug Olympics", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Several rows of white pills on a blue background.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/sUb9BUO8vFHs8YQxUQRjmB40T3g=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73098103/Vrg_Illo_226056_K_Radtke_Pill.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>I have some proposed enhancements. | Kristen Radtke / The Verge; Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"qBOGPw\">In a case of life imitating <em>Saturday Night Live, </em>Peter Thiel has invested in a seed round of the Enhanced Games, which describes itself as \u201cthe modern reinvention of the Olympic Games that does not have drug testing.\u201d</p>\n<div id=\"PGVEQa\"><div style=\"width: 100%; height: 0; padding-bottom: 56.25%;\"></div></div>\n<p id=\"yCb4j5\">It does seem to go a little beyond just not testing, though, at least <a href=\"https://enhanced.org/2024/01/29/seedfundingannouncement/\">judging by the press release</a>. The investors \u201csee the vision of a new model of sports, that openly celebrates sci", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T21:21:17+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055857/peter-thiel-enhanced-games-peds-olympics", "permanent": false}, {"title": "If you have an Arlo camera or video doorbell, it\u2019s about to get more expensive", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Arlo\u2019s Essential wired video doorbell installed on a front door.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/A9Q9pXVGqoZ5eOs2tJK2GL28UYQ=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73098094/jtuohy_220222_5043_0004.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>Arlo\u2019s cloud subscription plan for a single camera or video doorbell is increasing to $7.99 a month.</em> | Photo by Jennifer Pattison Tuohy / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"1a4b9N\">In more \u201cthings are just getting expensive\u201d news, the Arlo Secure subscription service is climbing. Again. This time, it\u2019s going from $4.99 to $7.99 for a single camera or video doorbell. This 60 percent price hike comes on the heels of an increase early last year from $2.99 to $4.99. </p>\n<p id=\"M83DRH\">According to an email sent to single-camera users from Arlo and <a href=\"https://www.reddit.com/r/arlo/comments/1aeb247/wtf_whos_canceling_their_single_camera_plan/\">posted on Reddit</a>, the chan", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T21:19:49+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055880/arlo-secure-security-camera-price-increase", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Microsoft\u2019s gaming revenues overtake Windows thanks to Activision Blizzard", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Illustration of Microsoft\u2019s Windows logo\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/I8tEtHe59eVJG_bk1iMVdFHqa9E=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73098022/acastro_STK109_microsoft_02.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Alex Castro / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"OoFhyf\">Microsoft <a href=\"https://click.linksynergy.com/deeplink?id=nOD%2FrLJHOac&amp;mid=24542&amp;u1=verge&amp;murl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.microsoft.com%2Fen-us%2Finvestor%2Fearnings%2Ffy-2024-q2\" rel=\"sponsored nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\">just posted</a> the second quarter of its 2024 fiscal financial results. The software maker made $62 billion in revenue and a net income of $21.9 billion during Q2. Revenue is up 18 percent, and net income has increased by 33 percent. </p>\n<p id=\"eyvUjj\">This is the first quarter Microsoft is reporting earnings as a <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/24/24049285/microsoft-3-trillion-dollar-mar", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T21:06:12+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055445/microsoft-q2-2024-earnings-revenue-profits-windows-xbox-gaming-surface", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Art collective MSCHF is streaming movies like Barbie in ASCII for free", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/-LLtwqjGo2gWdySn5qoLgSpEwtU=/82x0:1000x612/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73097528/Screen_Shot_2024_01_29_at_9.03.30_AM.0.png\" />\n        <figcaption>MSCHF</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"d1Zl8E\">The art collective MSCHF is stirring up some trouble on the internet again. For its latest project, <a href=\"https://ascii.theater/\">ASCII Theater</a>, the group will broadcast a popular new film daily in ASCII format that anyone can watch for free. Just <a href=\"https://ascii.theater/\">paste the command</a> on your Mac or PC\u2019s terminal, and you can watch films like<em> Barbie</em> exactly as, well, virtually no one has intended. </p>\n<p id=\"7aFSzK\">ASCII art films are nothing new and date back to the early days of the internet. They are made by converting a film, frame by frame, into lines of text characters. Instead of pixels, you\u2019ll see text. One of the most famous examples is the ASCII art v", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T19:00:00+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055041/ascii-theater-mschf-copyright-law-barbie-film-streaming", "permanent": false}, {"title": "How to stop location tracking on your Android phone (mostly)", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/HQvSX9yTWz03Njmtu8yvH0Vksnc=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/67293304/acastro_180413_1777_android_0001.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Alex Castro / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"tJmXXh\">Location tracking can be very handy \u2014 it\u2019s convenient when an app can tell you, say, where the nearby restaurants or gas stations are \u2014 but it\u2019s also a privacy issue (something that at least one of Google\u2019s competitors <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2023/11/2/23943245/android-is-a-massive-tracking-device\">has used in its sales pitch</a>).</p>\n<p id=\"GalrTP\">You probably know that Google can track your location and movements through its Google Maps app. But you may not realize that your Android phone is <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2018/8/13/17684660/google-turn-off-location-history-data\">also tracking your movements and activities</a> through several other b", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T18:52:39+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/21401280/android-location-tracking-history-stop-how-to", "permanent": false}, {"title": "The New York Times is building a team to explore AI in the newsroom", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"The New York Times HQ logo (1020)\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/KGr2PNN3-Rg6EA14vwVn5QvZqjk=/3x0:1017x676/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73097381/nytimes-logo-headquarters-stock_1020.0.jpg\" />\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"OpsbAY\"><em>The New York Times</em> will begin building a team to explore the use of generative AI in its newsroom. Zach Seward, who was recently <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2023/12/12/23998421/the-new-york-times-has-hired-someone-to-head-up-ai-initiatives\">hired by the publication</a> to head AI initiatives, <a href=\"https://www.threads.net/@zseward/post/C2upYZZOEVT\">posted on Threads</a> that the team will be \u201cfocused on prototyping uses of generative AI and other machine-learning techniques to help with reporting and how the <em>Times</em> is presented to readers.\u201d </p>\n<p id=\"lMyNtH\">Seward\u2019s post said the <em>Times</em> plans to hire a machine learning engineer, a software engineer, a designer, and ", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T18:16:03+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055718/new-york-times-generative-ai-machine-learning", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Infinite Wealth can drag on but makes up for it with heart, soul, and Pok\u00e9mon", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Screenshot from Like a Dragon: Infinite Wealth featuring the game\u2019s protagonist, Ichiban Kasuga, taking a cellphone selfie with a puppy filter\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/EchfmKFWUMosUMNNmLYueNCniX0=/150x0:1770x1080/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73097211/18d5b12a78a80_screenshotUrl.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: Sega</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n\n  \t\t <p>Infinite Wealth is several different games wrapped up in a  hard-hitting social commentary package.</p>\n  <p>\n    <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24055072/like-a-dragon-infinite-wealth-review-yakuza-sega\">Continue reading&hellip;</a>\n  </p>", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T17:30:00+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24055072/like-a-dragon-infinite-wealth-review-yakuza-sega", "permanent": false}, {"title": "The Ministry Of Ungentlemanly Warfare is ready to get its hands dirty in new trailer", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/3u2KnEVndjIqaI9PZODpi_QH4PQ=/548x0:2333x1190/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73097199/Screen_Shot_2024_01_30_at_10.54.57_AM.0.png\" />\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"74ngSG\">After a lifetime of <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2015/12/28/10675580/christopher-nolan-wwii-movie-dunkirk-65mm-film-imax\">World War II movies</a>, we\u2019ve all heard and seen stories about how the Allied powers defeated the Nazis in large-scale battles. But Lionsgate\u2019s upcoming action / comedy <em>The Ministry of Ungentlemanly Warfare </em>from <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/12/13253732/guy-ritchie-director-live-action-aladdin-disney\">director Guy Ritchie</a> seems like the sort of feature that might throw audiences for a loop \u2014 if not for its slick action sequences, then for the way it\u2019s inspired by a true story.</p>\n<p id=\"ynbQAu\">Set against the backdrop of WWII as Hitler\u2019s influence continued to spread across Euro", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T17:22:25+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24055597/the-ministry-of-ungentlemanly-warfare-trailer", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Today is the last day to score preorder promos on the Galaxy S24 series", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra showing always on display with dimmed wallpaper and widgets.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/BdP1vBiBKVdmXlQ9WiLs8Qux0do=/0x0:2000x1333/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73097121/DSC06525.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>Samsung\u2019s Galaxy S24 Ultra is the largest and most capable phone in the lineup.</em> | Photo by Allison Johnson / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"5cgLDa\">Decent deals on new gadgets aren\u2019t always easy to come by, which is why we love a good preorder promotion. Samsung has offered some pretty solid ones in recent years and, true to form, is discounting the entire Galaxy S24 lineup ahead of its launch tomorrow, January 31st.</p>\n<div class=\"c-float-left c-float-hang\"><aside id=\"k178sd\"><div></div></aside></div>\n<p id=\"RlqZoP\">Additionally, retailers like Amazon and Best Buy are offering similar storage upgrades and gift cards, regardless of whether you purchase the Samsung", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T17:00:00+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24050368/samsung-galaxy-s24-plus-ultra-preorder-gift-card-deal-sale", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Why Sen. Brian Schatz thinks child safety bills can trump the First Amendment", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A portrait of Sen. Brian Schatz of Hawaii.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/WfVx0GfWwJFaTPnBE_gGu1lcSZY=/0x0:3000x2000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73097120/VRG_DCD_Brian_Schatz.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Photo illustration: The Verge | Photo Tom Williams / CQ-Roll Call, Inc. via Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n\n  \t\t <p>The Democratic senator from Hawaii on regulating social media: \u2018An algorithm doesn\u2019t have a First Amendment right.\u2019</p>\n  <p>\n    <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24054658/senator-brian-schatz-congress-kosa-first-amendment-regulation-decoder-interview\">Continue reading&hellip;</a>\n  </p>", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T17:00:00+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24054658/senator-brian-schatz-congress-kosa-first-amendment-regulation-decoder-interview", "permanent": false}, {"title": "FEMA will pay states to install solar panels and heat pumps", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Puerto Rico Faces Extensive Damage After Hurricane Maria\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/PMnfu1F84iPLajBYV6YxMz-5ZRM=/0x0:5400x3600/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73097081/858810706.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>People sit in their home lit by a single donated solar lamp more than two weeks after Hurricane Maria hit the island on October 7th, 2017, in San Isidro, Puerto Rico.&nbsp;</em> | Photo by Mario Tama / Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"wU006T\">The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) <a href=\"https://www.fema.gov/press-release/20240130/biden-harris-administration-announces-new-actions-help-communities-reduce\">announced</a> today that it\u2019ll start reimbursing local governments for installing solar panels and more efficient appliances after a disaster strikes. </p>\n<p id=\"FID2VA\">The move can help communities prepare for another calamity by equipping them with tools that just might keep the lig", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T16:50:31+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055546/fema-solar-panel-pay-costs-disaster-reimbursement", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Your home network might soon get a new \u2014 and simpler \u2014 name", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"An illustration showing a repeating pattern of blue Wi-Fi logos\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/kpneFBhBhyXRwmy8U_ANL0dqvgY=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73097016/acastro__171016_1777_0001_v7.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustrator by Alex Castro / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"CfifxV\">ICANN, the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers, <a href=\"https://itp.cdn.icann.org/en/files/root-system/identification-tld-private-use-24-01-2024-en.pdf\">is proposing a change</a> that could streamline the way you access your home\u2019s internal network. That means, instead of using the 192.168.x.x address to configure your router, you\u2019d just need to type .internal.</p>\n<p id=\"cXqLi1\">As pointed out by <a href=\"https://www.theregister.com/2024/01/29/icann_internal_tld/\"><em>The Register</em></a>, ICANN\u2019s Security and Stability Advisory Committee (SSAC) first identified a need to reserve a top-leve", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T16:36:41+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055534/web-private-network-internal-icann-name", "permanent": false}, {"title": "The latest iPad Air has dropped to an all-time low", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"The 2022 iPad Air\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/AZK2Ay9Kk_JxZj0xyQQ2bQK7ZEk=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73096765/akrales_220314_5071_0026.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>The fifth-gen iPad Air is available at Best Buy starting at just $449.99.</em> | Image: Amelia Holowaty Krales / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"Y4s1dT\">In case you haven\u2019t heard, Apple might be dropping the new iPad Air at the <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/28/24053334/apples-next-ipads-are-likely-due-at-the-end-of-march\">end of March</a>. The <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2023/12/6/23990883/apple-ipad-air-oled-pro-spring-release-12-9-inch\">rumored, next-gen iPad Air</a> is said to come in two configurations, one of which will supposedly boast a larger 12.9-inch display like the iPad Pro. Even if it is released later this year, though, it\u2019s not likely to receive any major discounts for a while, making the c", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T15:36:53+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24054324/apple-ipad-air-m1-aqara-smart-lock-u100-google-pixel-8-deal-sale", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Universal\u2019s next big park will include werewolves, dragons, and Super Mario", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A photo of a piranha plant at Super Nintendo World.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/wYlyxPBQ2PdsbI7JI-olKr8X60U=/0x0:8256x5504/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73096734/SUPER_NINTENDO_WORLD_land_at_USH__2_.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: NBCUniversal</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"C1yr6k\">As in California, so must be in Florida. We knew<em> Super Mario</em> was coming to Florida, and now we know when, but we also got a lot more details on the park overall. Super Nintendo World will be a part of Universal Orlando Resort\u2019s brand-new theme park, dubbed Universal Epic Universe. </p>\n<p id=\"hgY1M3\">Five different worlds will make up the park. There\u2019s Super Mario World, a new <em>Harry Potter </em>world, a <em>How to Train Your Dragon</em> world, and a Dark Universe world that just might explain where all that <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/8/16610248/universal-dark-universe-monsterverse-alex-kurtzman-chris-mor", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T15:29:14+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24055456/super-nintendo-world-universal-epic-universe-florida", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Tesla\u2019s next-generation vehicle: all the news about Elon Musk\u2019s next big EV bet", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/UAozd0GqQkMpm5cpRE_mg9Ac-2w=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73096722/acastro_180430_1777_tesla_0002.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Alex Castro / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p>Will it be the Model 2? Model C? Whatever it\u2019s called, Tesla\u2019s long-promised $25,000 EV could be a game-changer. </p>\n  <p>\n    <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24054854/tesla-next-generation-vehicle-ev-elon-musk\">Continue reading&hellip;</a>\n  </p>", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T15:22:41+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24054854/tesla-next-generation-vehicle-ev-elon-musk", "permanent": false}, {"title": "AT&T launches branded calls to help filter out spam", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A person wearing earbuds walks past a storefront with the AT&amp;amp;T logo above the person\u2019s head.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/74SrhqWcPFaz-Y5NJInFoakAi7Y=/88x0:4912x3216/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73096640/1956320743.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>A person walks past an AT&amp;T store in midtown Manhattan on January 23rd, 2024, in New York City.</em> | Photo by Kena Betancur / VIEWpress / Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"IKkzfK\">In a move that\u2019s supposed to help people screen spammy phone calls, AT&amp;T announced a new service today that allows businesses to make branded calls. If a business opts in to the program and calls an AT&amp;T wireless customer, its brand name and logo will pop up on the receiving phone.</p>\n<p id=\"PhBBrm\">It\u2019s the latest <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2022/12/29/23531770/google-voice-spam-call-warning-enhanced-protection\">attempt</a> at <a href=\"https://www.thever", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T14:55:55+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055438/branded-phone-calls-spam-robocall-att-transunion", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Apple Vision Pro review: magic, until it\u2019s not", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<p>The Apple Vision Pro is the best consumer headset anyone\u2019s ever made \u2014 and that\u2019s the problem.</p>\n  <p>\n    <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24054862/apple-vision-pro-review-vr-ar-headset-features-price\">Continue reading&hellip;</a>\n  </p>", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T14:00:00+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24054862/apple-vision-pro-review-vr-ar-headset-features-price", "permanent": false}, {"title": "My new favorite way to manage my family\u2019s calendars is getting bigger", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A digital calendar on a wall in a home.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/YG2zoBPQbc4HTB_htP_3GoCCnDQ=/460x0:3700x2160/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73096324/Cal_Max_hallway.0.png\" />\n        <figcaption><em>Skylight Calendar Max is a digital family calendar designed to blend into your home.</em> | Image: Skylight</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"BwfsRc\">Smart photo frame company <a href=\"https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;xs=1&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.skylightframe.com%2F&amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;sref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theverge.com%2F2024%2F1%2F30%2F24054438%2Fskylight-cal-max-smart-family-calendar-launch-pricing\" rel=\"sponsored nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Skylight</a> is launching a new version of its Skylight Calendar, a smart family calendar. The <a href=\"https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;xs=1&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.skylightframe.com%2Fcalmax&amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T12:20:00+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24054438/skylight-cal-max-smart-family-calendar-launch-pricing", "permanent": false}, {"title": "Yelp will use AI to tell you if that burger\u2019s any good", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/HGGKWtCdI8bvkYkfRb3FkBU3TZw=/0x133:700x600/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73096271/yelp_ai_reviews_2.0.jpg\" />\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"cLhPan\">Yelp is joining the wealth of platforms expanding their use of AI, as it\u2019s <a href=\"https://blog.yelp.com/news/winter-product-release-2024\">rolling out a new feature</a> on iOS that rounds up and summarizes user reviews in a blurb that appears near the top of a company\u2019s Yelp page.</p>\n<p id=\"bV9X8O\">The new feature uses large language models (LLMs) to parse through user feedback to highlight \u201cwhat the business is best known for based on first-hand reviews,\u201d Yelp says. That may include a mention of a location\u2019s atmosphere, popular dishes, amenities, and more. One example (as shown in the image at the top of this article) describes a restaurant as a \u201cretro diner well known for its classic cheeseburgers and affordable prices.\u201d</p>\n  <figure class=\"e-imag", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T12:00:00+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24054806/yelp-ai-business-summary-reviews", "permanent": false}, {"title": "TikTok test automatically identifies products in videos and offers purchase links", "comments": [], "bookmarked": false, "user": null, "dead": false, "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "age": null, "page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "language": "en", "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "page_rating_visits": 0, "artist": null, "vote": 0, "source_obj__id": 61, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Three screens showing some of what shopping on TikTok on your phone look like.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/HTY07_SXW9edgtdVi-TAj-PWbRA=/56x0:2024x1312/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73096238/Ways_to_Shop_White_Background.0.png\" />\n        <figcaption><em>An example of how product links currently appear in TikTok after the launch of TikTok Shop.</em> | Image: TikTok</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"zJ7eLC\">TikTok Shop links could soon become a lot more common across the social media app. <a href=\"https://archive.ph/lWCAu\"><em>Bloomberg</em> reports</a> that the company is testing a new feature that automatically identifies products in the platform\u2019s videos before offering a link to \u201cFind similar items on TikTok Shop.\u201d A spokesperson for the company was not immediately available to respond to <em>The Verge\u2019s</em> request for comment, but it confirmed to <em>Bloomberg</em> that the feature is an early test.</p>\n<p id=\"w", "page_rating": 0, "date_published": "2024-01-30T11:21:55+00:00", "tags": [], "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/30/24055388/tiktok-shoppable-videos-automatic-product-discovery", "permanent": false}]